On Jan. 31, Italy declared a state of emergency and grounded flights to and from China. Friends told me that many Chinese were stranded in Italy, including her former colleague, Xiang Ge.

Xiangge and I got in touch on Feb. 4, when he had left Italy for Abu Dhabi, where the direct flight to China was still open. He told me that the Emirates had just suspended all flights to and from China except Beijing. As the day went on, he worried that he would go from being stuck in Italy to being stuck in the Middle East.

When it comes to his experiences in Italy, the words he repeatedly refers to are "discrimination" and "self-help" .

This article is based on Xiangge's dictation, collation and composition

01

Overnight, a state of emergency was declared in Italy

When I went abroad (January 21) , Wuhan was not closed and there was little news coverage. As I recall, it was just a regional flu.

I stayed in the Czech Republic for a few days, then I went to Italy (January 27) . Italy is warm and sunny in winter with little rain. The people there are very friendly, they like to talk rather than the English are cranky.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Italian street scene

A luxury goods clerk told me that a bus carrying a Wuhan Tour Group had been spotted on a highway near Florence with a fever. Called 911, got the whole highway shut down.

Back at my hotel each night for two days, I watched CNN and BBC news (since they were the only English channels) , alternately "impeaching trump" and "Wuhan pneumonia" . Later, the Wuhan more and more space, and a BBC reporter wanted to break into the gold and Silver Pool Hospital, was stopped by armed police.

At first I was glad I had escaped the plague by traveling. Things took a turn for the worse, and on January 30th Italy appeared on CNN. Two tourists from Wuhan were diagnosed in Rome, and 7,000 people on board the Costa cruises off the Italian coast were stranded on what appeared to be a Hong Kong couple called the new crown. On the same day, the World Health Organization (hereinafter referred to as the "World Health Organization Organization") the "new crown" epidemic as a public health emergency of international concern.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
About 7,000 people, including crew and passengers, were detained on the ship for about 12 hours, the Costa Emerald confirmed. Only after the test result was negative did the passengers begin to be allowed to pass.

On top of that, Italy declared a state of emergency overnight, grounding all flights to and from China.

I've only been in Rome for two days, and before I've even started playing, I realize I can't go back.

02

Call the embassy

Immediately after the grounding, I began to study how to transfer back from a third country.

Unfortunately, as soon as the World Health Organization news came out, many countries were grounded, and BA was the first to do so. I read on Weibo that many Chinese stranded in Italy went overnight to Madrid, Frankfurt and Amsterdam, hoping for a direct flight to China, from which their return ticket was sold to thirty-six thousand. And when they got there, they said, "the flight's canceled. ".

My Air China flight gave me two options: a refund and a free change to a flight within five months.

I asked: "So this is not let me stay three or four months, visa expired what to do? "

"Ask the Italian customs or immigration authorities, " they said

Italian English sounds a bit laborious, probably they listen to my English also laborious. We always got off on the wrong foot, so I called the Chinese Embassy in Italy.

The line is busy all the time.

I was eating in a restaurant in Venice, and every once in a while I picked up my phone and called again. I was sitting next to two Englishmen who said, in a very authentic British accent:

"The Chinese eat bats. They deserve to get it. "

"It is God's punishment for them to destroy nature and animals in this way. "

The call finally went through.

The Embassy asked me if I was from Hubei and if I had any flu or fever. I said No. I asked if they would charter a plane to pick up the stranded Italians. They said they are contacting, but may give priority to Hubei, other Hukou suggested to leave on their own, go to a third country transfer. I asked what other countries were available for transit. They said they could ask at the airport information desk.

Out of the restaurant, the roadside pigeons suddenly flew away in flocks.

"If only I could fly, " I thought.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Piazza Venezia, Italy

03

China Virus

February 1st was my fifth day in Italy.

"China Virus" ran on the front page of the local paper.

Italian Evening News, February 1st

The question I get asked the most these days is "Where are you from? " Where are you from

My Standard answer is: "China, but relax, not from Wuhan. " From China, relax, but I'm not from Wuhan

Outside Florence's LV stands a line of shop assistants wearing face masks, with only Chinese tourists still strolling in, making it rare to see foreigners. From a distance, it looks like the "isolation room" of the Chinese people.

More and more people are asking for help on Weibo. A blogger has formed a wechat group called "self-help team of stay in Italy" .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Screenshot of the stranded group announcement

After entering the group, I found that my situation is still good, many people in the group do not understand a word of English, they really do not know how to do. Some people in the group said that Sichuan Airlines originally wanted to pick up a group of stranded Chinese from Rome. The tickets were also quite cheap, more than 4,000 yuan, but the Italian authorities were very adamant that they would not allow the Chinese flights to land. In addition, we soon confirmed that both Emirates and Aeroflot are still able to fly to China. You know, they say that in times of trouble, you know, they're real brothers.

I bought a plane ticket to Abu Dhabi on February 3rd and to Beijing on February 6th.

On the bus to the airport, an old white lady saw me and suddenly put a scarf over her nose and ran out of the car. The other man in the car, who was reading the newspaper, glanced at me, too. I saw the front page of his newspaper read "stay away from the Chinese" . These two days, this kind of phenomenon is very common, some restaurants and hotels have written explicitly "no Chinese" ; my friend who studied in Italy said that the discrimination suffered by the Group of foreign students is very serious; Some of the friends in the support group were placed in the basement by the hotel.

"No Chinese tourists allowed" notice

Security was surprisingly lax, and I had expected "a state of emergency" to be tighter. They set up a separate security checkpoint for the Chinese, neither taking their temperature nor checking tax returns. It's not like when I used to come to Italy. I received a particularly clear message in this "Perk" : You have everything you need, so just go.

04

Via the United Arab Emirates

On the plane from Rome to Abu Dhabi, to my right, sat an American man, polite and unmasked.

He asked me where I was from, and I said China.

During our conversation, I learned that his wife was a member of the Mdecins Sans Frontires and was working on a similar disease in Africa.

"The virus in China is too clever to be seen at first, but it has spread to a lot of people later. "

"A lot of viral masks are unwatchable and, more importantly, wash your hands. "

"The Chinese government's reaction this time was better than I had expected. "

"I hope you made the right decision to come back. "

The Pink Polo Shirt, he muttered, made him more casual and chatty.

I frequently expressed my appreciation and gratitude to him. That's about the most objective statement and the most equal conversation I've heard in days.

When I got off the plane, I saw an announcement from the Emirates that all flights to and from China, except Beijing, would be suspended. I was worried: I wouldn't go from Italy to the Middle East.

Emirates

The United Arab Emirates is no less sensitive and vigilant than Italy about the Chinese outbreak. The airport was full of people wearing masks, as were the staff at mosques and museums. Every time we took a taxi, the driver would ask, "where are you from? " They put on their masks as soon as they learned I was from China, and one of them mumbled something, and I only remembered one word, "Dangerous. ".

I was on the Abu Dhabi Metro one time, and I heard two black guys talking.

"Don't you have a mask? "

"No. "

"Did you know there is a terrible virus from China? "

Then one handed the other a mask. They were standing right next to me. Maybe they thought I didn't understand English. I can also understand this kind of discrimination: It's a way for them to protect themselves. Foreigners avoid the Chinese, and some people avoid Wuhan, no one stands on the moral high ground.

The American friend said, "I hope you are right to go home. " I know he meant, "maybe you are better off in Europe. ". Which is the better choice? Which is more important, security or equality? Which is wiser, to flee or to return home? I thought about it all the way.

Sho's Emirates

On February 6, my flight took off as scheduled, and it was full of Chinese people. Reluctantly, the stewardess served us, and the overhead bell rang several times, but no one came. At a time when foreigners are turning their backs on foreigners, the people on this plane are O to go home.

The plane landed in Beijing with a slight cheer, and I felt lucky, too.

I think we have all the answers to those dilemmas.

Editor: Tong Zhi Heng Fa Chuen
